Authors: Anand, A.; Chandan, P.; Singh, R. B.
Title: Homestays at Korzok: Supplementing Rural Livelihoods and Supporting Green Tourism in the Indian Himalayas
Author_affil: Department of Geographical Sciences, University of Maryland
Desired_outcome: 1) protect the local wildlife and natural resources (Lake Tsomoriri, black-necked crane2) offer alternative livelihood opportunities
Int_notes: The homestay project is a green initiative based on equity, accountability and cooperation, and participation. They practice sustainability through these practices: 1) use of green, efficient, and renewable energy sources; 2) efficient water consumption and usage; 3) efficient waste management; 4) conservation of fragile ecosystem and biodiversity; 5) effective management of cultural heritage, traditional values, and promotion of intercultural understanding; 6) improving livelihoods and poverty reduction; 7) supporting women's income; and 8) shared learning and diffusion of ideas
Outcome_notes: The project has brought environmental, economic, and livelihood benefits to the people. Women are better able to fulfill their role as primary caregivers to children and the elderly. The economic standing of poor and marginalized as increased. The community is better able to secure rights. There is a more equitable, steady, and sustainable flow of income. The benefits of the program do not benefit everyone equally since some people do not have extra space or a permanent dwelling in the village.

Authors: Aswani, S.; Furusawa, T.
Title: Do Marine Protected Areas Affect Human Nutrition and Health? A Comparison between Villages in Roviana, Solomon Islands
Author_affil: Dept. of Antropology and Interdepartmental Graduate Program in Marine Science, University of California Santa Barbara
Funding: David and Lucile Packard Foundation (Grants 2001-17407, 2005-447628-58080), Conservation Internation GCF (Grant 227628-59102), Pew Fellowship in Marine Conservation 2005, NSF (Grant NSF-CAREER-BCS-0238539), John D. and Catharine T. MacArthur Foundation (Grant 60243), Japan Society for Promotion of Science
Desired_outcome: conserve vulnerable species and habitats (biodiversity and ecosystem function), protect susceptible life history stages (spawning and nursery grounds), enhance productivity of fisheries (food security), infrastructure development programs
Int_notes: Marine Protected Area
Study_location: Kozou, Nusa Hope, Baraulu, Olive, Dunde, Nuda Banga
Outcome_notes: Nutritional impact is dependent on other contextual factors beyond MPA effectiveness - incl. modernaization. Also recognize that the impact is not necessarily direct, no control for effects of on-going socioeconomic transformations that affect diet. Additionally that it also depends on MPA performance, whether biologically, MPAs are increasing resource biomass. Lastly, type of habitat covered by MPA also introduces variability of food availability and diet.

Authors: Emana, B.
Title: Final Evaluation of Pastoralist Food Security Partnership Project, Oromia Regional State, Ethiopia
Desired_outcome: Stabilize pastoral livelihoods; food security; Optimal use of naturalresources; improved livestock marketing and incomes diversified; and improved administrative capacity related to food security.
Equity_cat: Economic living standards
Summary: `!)Communities living in three conflict kebeles, namely, Alga, Bulbul and Kalada started to live peacefully due to the conflict resolution work of the project. Moreover, the worksignificantly reduced livestock theft by over 90% compared to the situation before theproject; Practices such as unprotected settlement in the rangelands, overgrazing, deforestation, bushencroachment, etc., significantly reduced in the pilot areas. Private Kallo system has beenabandoned and communal Kallo strengthened to ensure fair distribution and sustainable useof rangelands; developed the culture of cut and carry and storing hay to meet emergency feedrequirement. The cut and carry from Kallo also created new source of income for pastoralistswhen sold and increased livestock productivity when used as feed._ Natural resource based income generation activities opened-up new income generatingopportunities and livelihoods diversification, especially for the women and the poor. Theprospect of increased income and better way of life from these income sources depend onmarket linkage and further capacity building.

Authors: Jim, C.Y.; S.S. Xu
Title: Stifled stakeholders and subdued participation: Interpreting local responses toward Shimentai nature reserve in South China
Author_affil: Department of Geography, The University of Hong Kong, Pokfulam Road, Hong Kong.
Desired_outcome: Community participation in PA management
Summary: Many respondents had inadequate knowledge, understanding,and perceptions of the reserve. Although mostrespondents welcomed the expected park-related dividends,the most affected near-zone villagers anticipated losses dueto restriction on traditional resource-extraction activities in theforest. The local expectations were influenced by place of residence,emigration of rural young, and household affluence.The lack of local participation in management and inadequatedissemination of information posed obstacles to effectiveconservation. The high expectation of accruing benefitsfrom development projects, including tourism, mightbe misplaced and might not be realized.

Authors: Leisher, C., Brouwer, R., Boucher, T.M., Vogelij, R., Bainbridge, W.R., and Sanjayan, M.
Title: Striking a Balance: Socioeconomic Development and Conservation in Grassland through Community-Based Zoning
Desired_outcome: Grassland conservation and poverty reduction project; managed livestock grazing
Equity_cat: Environmental, Material living standards, Economic living standards
Summary: Ten years after project launch, we measured the ecological and socioeconomic impacts of the project using Normalized Differential Vegetation Index remote sensing data and over 500 household interviews, as compared with similar non-conserved areas. Zoned management of the Umgano area had resulted in between 9% and 17% greater average peak production in the grassland areas compared to control sites. There was also a 21% gain in incomes for the roughly one hundred people employed by the forestry efforts, when compared to others in their village.

Authors: Leisher, C., Hess, S., Sherwood, D., and Boucher, T.
Title: Report on the Ecological and Socioeconomic Assessments of the Quito Water Fund
Desired_outcome: Water fund
Summary: There is little doubt that water fund activities have generated benefits to local people. Interviewswith key people in four water fund communities highlighted a range of perceived socioeconomic benefits from water fundprojects including improved farming practices, reduced household expenses, and healthier diets. However, this assessmentdid not succeed in accomplishing a robust randomized household survey. Attempts to quantify socioeconomic benefits wereconfounded by the work of a number of other organizations engaged in similar activities in the same communities. Thewater fund communities are largely poor, indigenous, and within one to two hours’é drive from Quito. This makes thempopular with development organizations and government agencies. In one water fund village, local residents identified 20different organizations that had worked in their community in recent years. In both surveys and focus groups, respondentscould not reliably identify which benefits flowed from water fund projects and which came from projects funded by others.

Authors: Lescuyer, G.
Title: Sustainable Forest Management at the Local Scale: A Comparative Analysis of Community Forests and Domestic Forests in Cameroon
Funding: French National Research Agency under the Agriculture and Sustainable Development Program
Outcome1: 1. Natural capital (i.e. the natural resource stocks and environ- mental services from which resource flows and services useful for livelihoods are derived)
Outcome2: 2. Physical capital (i.e. the capital base that is essential for the pursuit of any livelihood strategy)
Outcome3: 3. Financial capital (i.e. savings, credit and other inflows)
Outcome4: 4. Human capital (i.e. the skills, knowledge, good health and physical capability needed for the successful pursuit of livelihood strategies)
Outcome5: 5. Social capital (i.e. the social resources upon which people draw when pursuing livelihood strategies requiring coordinated actions)
Pathway_notes: 1. Enforcing end of logging (protected areas) increased natural capital and decreased financial capital2. Weak progress in village infrastructure led to low rate of progress for physical capital 3. Creation of community forest resulted in creation of institutions, increasing human and social capital

Authors: Margoluis, R.A.
Title: Conservation for health: Exploring the association between the small-scale commercial utilization of non-timber forest resources and human health in a tropical forest biosphere reserve
Desired_outcome: Small-scale utilization of non-timber resource utilization in biosphere reserve
Study_location: Sierra de Las Minas biosphere reserve
Summary: This study was designed to investigate the association between natural resource use and human health in the Sierra de las Minas Biosphere Reserve of Guatemala. Its primary hypothesis was that the small-scale utilization of non-timber forest resources (NTFRs) by rural families has a positive impact on their quality-of-life as defined by indicators of health. A second hypothesis was that the knowledge of the relationships between the biological and physical environment and human health has a positive impact on indicators of health. A final hypothesis was that rural poor families with access to NTFRs that can be sold will intensify their exploitation of these resources according to available household labor in order to maximize cash income and profit The study showed that in combination with other economic activities, commercial NTFR use is an integral element of an effect strategy for maintaining subsistence. It was also demonstrated that those households where the father believes that there are relationships between the forest and water and the forest and health, have a lower probability of having malnourished children. Finally, the research demonstrated that families in the Sierra de las Minas appear not to be motivated by profit. Instead, they will expend only enough household labor as is necessary to maintain a subsistence level

Author_affil: Ontario Institute forStudies in Education,University of Toronto, and shehas worked as a researchconsultant for Africa 2000Network (UNDP) New York
Int_notes: the Network sought to operate inthose countries that were ecologically the most vulnerable andit primarily addressed farmers, given the looming crisis of foodinsecurity, environments at risk and rising poverty. Ten Africancountries were identified and approached to launch theNetwork. The Network, as a funding and operational agency,endeavoured to respond to the problems of grassroots communitiesin relation to their environment. Community based groups,NGOs and training-research institutes, working in the fields ofsustainable development and environmental protection, receivedtechnical and grant supports through the Network
Equity_cat: Economic living standards, Governance & empowerment, Education
Pathway_notes: Parks and PAs are centers of disturbance in social-ecological systemsLivelihoods diversification at the household level as an adaptive response to park-related disturbances

Authors: Schmitt, J.A.
Title: Improving conservation efforts in the Serengeti ecosystem, Tanzania: An examination of knowledge, benefits, costs, and attitudes
Desired_outcome: Community based conservation adjacent to Serengeti national park, biosphere reserve; fences-and-fines enforcement
Summary: In this paper,we sought evidence to determine whether or not these efforts have been successful. Theevidence from our data shows that conservation policies have not sufficiently changed thecost-benefit equation facing local people in a manner sufficient to deter illegal naturalresource use and promote conservation. The vast majority of local people do not evenknow of the protected areas near their villages. For those that do know of the areas, thereported level of benefits from conservation is moderate at best. These benefits are notconditional on conservation performance and are given at the village level, whichprevents individual choices from affecting benefits. The costs from conservation arehigh, with wildlife routinely causing crop damage and livestock depredation. Overall, thebenefits of resource use are higher than the costs. Antipoaching efforts appear to beinsufficient to deter many people from illegal natural resource use. Our findings supportand expand upon previous studies in the ecosystem that have also found the costs andbenefits facing local people are not conducive with conservation

Title: Attitudes of local people towards collective actionfor forest management: the case of participatory forest management in Dodola area in the Bale Mountains, Southern Ethiopia
Study_location: Dodola district, Bale Mountains, Oromia regional state
Study_notes: Stated study objectives:To describe the attitudes, norms, and perceived behavioural control (PBC) that underlie intention of local people to participate in planting activity in the management of the Dodola forest area as a common property resource.To describe the beliefs behind people’és attitude, norms, and PBC in relation to planting and the differences in these among different groups of local people.
Outcome1: 1. Perception of utility of conservation measures
Outcome_notes: Considers underlying factors leading to positive perceptions and increased or maintained participation.
Pathway_notes: Two factors with strongest effect in motivating households to participate - 1) role of planting in expanding forest area resulting in reduction of area to be considered for rent payment = less rent paid per household. 2) Positive perceptin of households on ability to carry out planting.Socio-economic factors underlying motivations to participate - 1) higher education 2) higher dependency on crop income

Authors: Wells, S.; Samoilys, M.; Makoloweka, S.; Kalombo, H.
Title: Lessons learnt from a collaborative management programme in coastal Tanzania
Desired_outcome: Collaborative coastal management; sustainable development
Summary: Determining whether this is due to TCZCDP interventions is not easy, as there was little socio-economic monitoring and thus no demonstrated links between management of marine resources and trends in household income. During the external evaluations, however, villagers and some government officials said that more children were going to school and had shoes, both of which relate to increased income. Changes in the form of new and improved houses, better clothing, and more cell phones and TVs were often mentioned [22]. Although the Programme was considered at least partly responsible for these perceptions, possibly because villagers now have greater control over the resources they use, there could be many other causes, such as the general improvement in the Tanzanian economy (economic growth rose by 4% in the 1990s to 6.7% in 2004 [25]) or the impacts of other donor-funded development projects such as the 1972_1991 Tanga Integrated Rural Development Programme (TIRDEP) funded by the then Federal Republic of Germany [26]. The monitoring results were insufficiently clear to demonstrate a direct positive effect of the CMAPs on fish catches and income

Title: Local impacts and responses to regional forest conservation and rehabilitation programs in China's northwest Yunnan province
Author_affil: World Agroforestry Centre, Floor 3, Building A, Zhonghuandasha, Yanjiadi 650034, Kunming, Yunnan Province, PR China
Desired_outcome: Regional forest conservation and restoration; Sloping Land Conversion Program (SLCP); National Forest Protection Program (NFPP)
Summary: he combination of the SLCP, in conjunction with the NFPP and the logging ban, has severely limited areas accessible for traditional herding and NTFP collection. This was a major concern for households without access to wage labour incomes. The paper argues that as well-intentioned as the programs are, they fail to accomplish the envisaged goal of mitigating erosion and surface flow in upper watersheds and subsequently having a positive impact in flood plains and preventing floods. In addition, it also reveals some of the negative impacts on livelihoods of mountain communities, their environment and overall agro-biodiversity.

Desired_outcome: Ecotourism; economic benefits; conservation incentives
Equity_cat: Economic living standards
Summary: In all five study cases, local residentsreceive significant benefits that out-competeother income sources. Income disparities betweenvillages are better explained by different degreesof tourism specialisation than by a varying degreeof autonomy from tourist agencies. (1) in villages specialised intourism, income flows raised environmentalawareness and gave incentives for a new rationalityin traditional resource use; (2) tourism incomeis less likely to reverse non-traditional, degradingdevelopment patterns in advanced stages; (3)tourism income can help to unite actors andstrengthen the raison d’ée_tre of a protected areathreatened by competing land uses

Authors: Yemiru, T.; Roos, A.; Campbell, B. M.; Bohlin, F.
Title: Forest incomes and poverty alleviation under participatory forest management in the bale highlands, Southern Ethiopia
Author_affil: Department of Forest Products, Swedish university of Agricultural sciences, P.O.Box 7060, SE-750-07, Vallv_gen 9A,Uppsala, Sweden
Desired_outcome: Participatory forest management; forest income; poverty alleviation
Equity_cat: Economic living standards
Summary: This study investigates the contribution of forest resources to the livelihoods of rural households under a participatorymanagement arrangement in southern Ethiopia. . Income data were collected in four separate seasons at intervals of three months. The result indicates that forest products are the most important sources of income contributing to 34% and 53% of household per capita income and per capita cash income, respectively. Forest income also helps 20% of the population to remain above the poverty line. Forest income reduces inequality (Gini coefficient) by 15.5%.

Authors: Zhou, D. Q.; Edward Grumbine, R.
Title: National parks in China: Experiments with protecting nature and human livelihoods in Yunnan province, Peoples' Republic of China (PRC)
Author_affil: Faculty of Environmental Science and Engineering, Kunming University of Science and Technology, 68 Wenchang Road, Yieryi Street, Kunming 650093, China
Desired_outcome: National park; policy and establishment; livelihoods
Study_location: Laojun Mountain National Park; Pudacuo National Park
Summary: This brief review of Yunnan’és ongoing experiment with nationalparks shows clearly that international concepts and expectationsabout nature reserves, when fed into China’és current cultural andpolitical conditions, may not be as serviceable as they are in theiroriginal context. we see little evidence so far that the pilotnational parks by themselves can resolve China’és nature reserveissues of unclear lines of administrative authority, inadequatefunding, poor professional capacity, and lack of community participation. Funding policies directly impact the level of financial benefitsthat reach local peoples in the communities surrounding Yunnan’ésnational parks. Though the pilots have been designed to improvelocal livelihoods by providing monies from park tourism receipts,provincial regulations make clear that the majority of income goesto tourism companies (ROPGYP, 2010: p. 147). Authors: Zulu, L.C.
Title: Re-scaling conservation: The political ecology of community based forest management in southern Malawi
Desired_outcome: Community-based forest management; charcoal production
Study_location: Blantyre City Fuelwoo Project, southern Malawi
Summary: Results indicate widespread failure and a backlash to the CBFM model. The model created scalar mismatches among forest ecology, deforestation processes, social organization, and institutional conservation arrangements, whose net effect was to undermine social and conservation goals. Land cover and spatial pattern analysis with satellite imagery showed that 44% of the area had undergone significant forest degradation, and revealed two distinct deforestation processes in the east and west side. For the eastern peri-urban villages, juxtaposition of poverty and exogenous market forces for wood overwhelmed CBFM institutions, and fueled unsustainable forest "mining."

Title: Poverty Alleviation in Tanzania - Forest Reserve Access for villagers of Kidabaga
Desired_outcome: Poverty alleviation; Forest protection
Equity_cat: Material living standards, Governance & empowerment
Summary: JFM aims at conserving NDUFR as well as alleviating the poverty of the villagers living adjacent to state owned forest reserve. The rural communities’é conserve the forest reserve, and gain legitimate access in return. This access consists of restricted user rights to the reserve with respect to the collection of firewood and Non-Wood Forest Products. INCOME GENERATING ACTIVITIES Income generating activities implemented as a part of the JFM scheme aim at substituting some forest products that the rural villagers are not allowed to take from the reserve. The activities on beekeeping and fish ponds are difficult to start as they are having a high entry cost as materials are needed. On the contrary, woodlots are common to most of the households and a good investment. MAIN FINDINGS The legitimate access to NDUFR has become stratified access. Stratified because different households are perceiving the legitimate access as either an obstacle or a possibility; and they make use of the forest reserve according to this perception. ACCESS TO KNOWLEDGE AND AUTHORITIES The households that perceive JFM as an obstacle are experiencing difficulties, when it comes to access to knowledge and access to authorities. Other households possess of social capital that facilitates their access to authorities and thereby also access to important knowledge about forest use and regulations.
